{
  "body": "In practice, I've found the [`polymod`](https://docs.perl6.org/routine/polymod) method to be good for two things:\r\n\r\n1. Decomposing a quantity into a compound quantity with multiple units:  \r\n  `my ($sec, $min, $hrs, $days, $weeks) = $seconds.polymod(60, 60, 24, 7);`  \r\n  `my ($B, $KiB, $MiB, $GiB, $TiB) = $bytes.polymod(1024 xx 5);`\r\n\r\n2. Getting the digits of a number in an arbitrary base:  \r\n  `my @digits-in-base37 = $number.polymod(37 xx *);`\r\n\r\nThe documentation currently presents use-case (1), but not (2).",
